\begin_layout Standard
In 2005, Kane and Mele [
\color blue
PRL 95, 226801 (2005)
\color inherit
] generalized the Haldane model to the graphene lattice model with the time
 reversal invariant spin-orbit coupling, which is known as the Kane-Mele
 model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The graphene lattice has the following translation vectors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{a}_{1}=a(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\ \frac{3}{2}),\qquad\bm{a}_{2}=a(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\ \frac{3}{2})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the bond length.
 The fractional coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 sites are written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{r}_{A}=(\frac{1}{3},\ \frac{1}{3}),\qquad\bm{r}_{B}=(\frac{2}{3},\ \frac{2}{3})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Kane-Mele model is expressed as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}=t\sum_{\langle i,j\rangle}c_{i}^{\dagger}c_{j}+i\lambda_{SO}\sum_{\langle\langle i,j\rangle\rangle}v_{ij}c_{i}^{\dagger}s_{z}c_{j}+i\lambda_{R}\sum_{\langle i,j\rangle}c_{i}^{\dagger}(\bm{s}\times\bm{d}_{ij})_{z}c_{j}+\lambda_{v}\sum_{i}\xi_{i}c_{i}^{\dagger}c_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{\dagger}=(c_{i,\uparrow}^{\dagger},c_{i,\downarrow}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 and the Pauli matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 describe the electron spin.
 The first term is the nearest neighbor hopping term on a graphene lattice.
 The second term is a mirror symmetric spin-orbit interaction which connects
 second neighbors with a spin dependent amplitude.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{ij}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}(\bm{d}_{i}\times\bm{d}_{j})_{z}=\pm1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{d}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{d}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are two unit vectors along the two bonds the electron traverses going from
 site 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The third term is the nearest neighbor Rashba term, which violates the
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{z}$
\end_inset

 mirror symmetry, breaks the conservation of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{z}$
\end_inset

 and couples the electrons with spin-up and spin-down.
 The last term is a staggered sublattice potential with 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}$
\end_inset

 breaks time-reversal symmetry, which allows the terms in the Hamiltonian
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{B}=\sum_{i}c_{i}^{\dagger}(\bm{B}\cdot\bm{s})c_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
